<section id="introduction">
      <h2>Introduction</h2>
      <p>Chinese civilisation is conventionally organised by <strong>dynasties</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">朝代</span>, <span class="pinyin">cháodài</span>) — successive ruling houses that governed all or part of China. This page surveys the major dynasties from the semi-legendary Xia through the Ming, focusing on each dynasty's contributions to the cultural traditions explored across this site: the <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac</a>, the <a href="/calendar/">calendar</a>, <a href="/fengshui/">feng shui</a>, <a href="/tcm/">medicine</a>, <a href="/taoism/">philosophy</a>, <a href="/martial-arts/">martial arts</a>, and the arts.</p>
      <p>The narrative ends at the Ming Dynasty (1644) — the last dynasty ruled by Han Chinese — consistent with this site's focus on pre-Qing cultural heritage.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="xia">
      <h2>Xia Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">夏朝</span>, c. 2070–1600 BCE)</h2>
      <p>The Xia is traditionally regarded as China's first dynasty, founded by Yu the Great (<span class="chinese-char">大禹</span>, <span class="pinyin">Dà Yǔ</span>) after he controlled the Great Flood. While archaeological evidence for the Xia remains debated (the Erlitou site in Henan is the leading candidate), it holds foundational importance in Chinese historical consciousness.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Significance</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Calendar origins</strong> — The traditional <em>Xia Xiao Zheng</em> (<span class="chinese-char">夏小正</span>, "Lesser Calendar of Xia") describes agricultural activities month by month, suggesting early calendar development. The <a href="/calendar/">Chinese calendar</a> is still sometimes called the "Xia calendar" (<span class="chinese-char">夏曆</span>).</li>
        <li><strong>Bronze Age transition</strong> — Early bronze production marks the beginning of China's Bronze Age civilisation</li>
        <li><strong>Hereditary succession</strong> — The Xia established dynastic succession (replacing the earlier abdication system), setting the pattern for all subsequent dynasties</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="shang">
      <h2>Shang Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">商朝</span>, c. 1600–1046 BCE)</h2>
      <p>The Shang is the earliest Chinese dynasty confirmed by contemporary archaeological evidence, centred on the Yellow River basin in modern Henan province. Its capital at Yinxu (<span class="chinese-char">殷墟</span>, near Anyang) has yielded extraordinary finds.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Oracle bone script (<span class="chinese-char">甲骨文</span>)</strong> — The earliest Chinese writing, inscribed on turtle shells and animal bones for divination. These contain the first written <a href="/calendar/">calendar records</a>, astronomical observations, and the <strong>Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天干地支</span>) system that remains the foundation of Chinese astrology.</li>
        <li><strong>Bronze casting</strong> — Shang bronze ritual vessels (ding, gui, jue) reached an artistic and technical sophistication unmatched in the ancient world. The Simuwu ding (<span class="chinese-char">司母戊鼎</span>) weighs 832 kg — the largest ancient bronze vessel ever found.</li>
        <li><strong>Divination</strong> — Systematic oracle bone divination (<span class="chinese-char">卜</span>, bǔ) established the precedent for the Chinese metaphysical tradition, influencing the later development of the <a href="/yijing/">Yi Jing</a>, <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a>, and <a href="/qimen/">Qi Men Dun Jia</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>Ancestor worship</strong> — The Shang formalised ancestral veneration, a practice that profoundly shaped Chinese civilisation and remains central to <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> observance.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="zhou">
      <h2>Zhou Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">周朝</span>, 1046–256 BCE)</h2>
      <p>The longest dynasty in Chinese history, the Zhou is divided into <strong>Western Zhou</strong> (1046–771 BCE, strong central authority) and <strong>Eastern Zhou</strong> (771–256 BCE), which is further subdivided into the <strong>Spring and Autumn period</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">春秋</span>, 770–476 BCE) and the <strong>Warring States period</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">戰國</span>, 475–221 BCE).</p>

      <h3>The Philosophical Golden Age</h3>
      <p>The Eastern Zhou — an era of political fragmentation and intellectual ferment — produced the <strong>Hundred Schools of Thought</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">百家爭鳴</span>, <span class="pinyin">Bǎijiā Zhēngmíng</span>), the greatest flowering of Chinese philosophy:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Confucianism</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">儒家</span>) — Confucius (<span class="chinese-char">孔子</span>, 551–479 BCE) and Mencius (<span class="chinese-char">孟子</span>, 372–289 BCE) established the ethical framework that would govern Chinese society for two millennia</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/taoism/">Taoism</a></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">道家</span>) — Laozi's <em>Daodejing</em> and Zhuangzi's philosophical writings created an alternative to Confucian social ethics, emphasising natural spontaneity and the Dao</li>
        <li><strong>Legalism</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">法家</span>) — Han Feizi and Shang Yang developed the political philosophy that enabled the Qin unification</li>
        <li><strong>Yin-Yang School</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">陰陽家</span>) — Zou Yan (<span class="chinese-char">鄒衍</span>, 305–240 BCE) systematised <a href="/wuxing/">Five Element theory</a> and the yin-yang cosmological framework that underpins Chinese astrology, medicine, and feng shui</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Other Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Yi Jing</strong> — The <a href="/yijing/">Book of Changes</a> was compiled during the Western Zhou, with its philosophical commentaries added during the Eastern Zhou</li>
        <li><strong>Mandate of Heaven</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天命</span>) — The political theory justifying dynastic change through moral authority rather than mere force</li>
        <li><strong>Ritual system (<span class="chinese-char">禮</span>)</strong> — The Zhou codified the ritual and ceremonial system, including <a href="/hanfu/">clothing regulations</a>, that defined Chinese civilisation</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="qin">
      <h2>Qin Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">秦朝</span>, 221–206 BCE)</h2>
      <p>Though lasting only 15 years, the Qin's impact was transformative. <strong>Qin Shi Huang</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">秦始皇</span>), the First Emperor, unified China for the first time and established the centralised imperial model that endured for over two thousand years.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Standardisation</strong> — Writing (the Small Seal script), weights, measures, currency, and axle widths were all standardised across the empire, enabling cultural unity</li>
        <li><strong>Calendar unification</strong> — The Qin imposed a unified <a href="/calendar/">calendar</a> across the empire, establishing the Zhuanxu calendar with the year beginning in the 10th month</li>
        <li><strong>The Terracotta Army</strong> — The First Emperor's mausoleum with 8,000+ life-sized warrior figures represents the scale of Qin ambition and artistic achievement</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/zodiac/">Zodiac evidence</a></strong> — Bamboo slips from Shuihudi (<span class="chinese-char">睡虎地</span>, 217 BCE) contain the earliest known complete zodiac animal cycle, confirming the system was established by the Qin period</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="han">
      <h2>Han Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">漢朝</span>, 206 BCE – 220 CE)</h2>
      <p>The Han Dynasty — divided into <strong>Western Han</strong> (206 BCE – 9 CE) and <strong>Eastern Han</strong> (25–220 CE) — established the identity of the Chinese people (who call themselves "Han" to this day). It was a period of territorial expansion, cultural confidence, and intellectual synthesis.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Confucian state orthodoxy</strong> — Emperor Wu (<span class="chinese-char">漢武帝</span>) established Confucianism as the official state philosophy, creating the imperial examination prototype and the scholarly class that would govern China</li>
        <li><strong>Calendar reform</strong> — The Taichu calendar (104 BCE) fixed the new year to the first lunar month, establishing the date for <a href="/spring-festival/">Chinese New Year</a> that persists today</li>
        <li><strong>Paper invention</strong> — Cai Lun (<span class="chinese-char">蔡倫</span>) improved paper-making technology (c. 105 CE), one of the most consequential inventions in human history</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/tcm/">Medical texts</a></strong> — The <em>Huangdi Neijing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">黃帝內經</span>) and <em>Shennong Bencao Jing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">神農本草經</span>) established the theoretical foundations of Chinese medicine</li>
        <li><strong>Silk Road</strong> — Zhang Qian's missions opened the <a href="/hanfu/">Silk Road</a> trade network, connecting China to Central Asia, Persia, and Rome</li>
        <li><strong>Sima Qian's <em>Shiji</em></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">史記</span>) — The first comprehensive Chinese history, establishing the historiographical tradition and recording the <a href="/martial-arts/#wuxia">knight-errant (俠)</a> tradition</li>
        <li><strong>Astronomy</strong> — Zhang Heng (<span class="chinese-char">張衡</span>) invented the armillary sphere and the world's first seismoscope, advancing the observational astronomy that informed the calendar</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="three-kingdoms">
      <h2>Three Kingdoms & Jin (<span class="chinese-char">三國·晉</span>, 220–420 CE)</h2>
      <p>The fall of the Han inaugurated centuries of division. The <strong>Three Kingdoms</strong> period (220–280 CE) — Wei, Shu, and Wu — is one of the most romanticised eras in Chinese history, immortalised in the novel <em>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</em> (<span class="chinese-char">三國演義</span>).</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="/tcm/">Zhang Zhongjing</a></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">張仲景</span>) — His <em>Shanghan Lun</em> (<span class="chinese-char">傷寒論</span>, c. 220 CE), written during the late Han/Three Kingdoms transition, remains the most clinically influential herbal medicine text in history</li>
        <li><strong>Hua Tuo</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">華佗</span>) — Legendary physician who developed anaesthesia (mafeisan, <span class="chinese-char">麻沸散</span>) and the Five Animal Frolics exercise system</li>
        <li><strong>Metaphysical philosophy</strong> — The <em>xuanxue</em> (<span class="chinese-char">玄學</span>, "dark learning") movement reinterpreted the <a href="/yijing/">Yi Jing</a> and <a href="/taoism/">Daoist</a> classics, profoundly influencing later Chinese thought</li>
        <li><strong>Buddhism's spread</strong> — Buddhism expanded rapidly during the period of division, eventually synthesising with native Chinese traditions to create uniquely Chinese Buddhist forms</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="sui-tang">
      <h2>Sui & Tang Dynasties (<span class="chinese-char">隋唐</span>, 581–907 CE)</h2>
      <p>The <strong>Sui Dynasty</strong> (581–618) reunified China after centuries of division. The <strong>Tang Dynasty</strong> (618–907) that followed is widely regarded as the zenith of Chinese civilisation — a cosmopolitan, culturally confident empire that was the world's wealthiest and most advanced society.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>BaZi development</strong> — Li Xuzhong (<span class="chinese-char">李虛中</span>) developed the <a href="/bazi/">Three Pillars</a> system of destiny analysis during the Tang, laying the groundwork for the full Four Pillars method refined in the Song</li>
        <li><strong>Poetry golden age</strong> — Li Bai (<span class="chinese-char">李白</span>), Du Fu (<span class="chinese-char">杜甫</span>), and Wang Wei (<span class="chinese-char">王維</span>) created the pinnacle of Chinese poetic art</li>
        <li><strong>Tang Code</strong> — The comprehensive legal code that influenced legal systems across East Asia</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/hanfu/">Fashion</a></strong> — The most cosmopolitan period in Chinese clothing history, absorbing Silk Road influences into a distinctively bold aesthetic</li>
        <li><strong>Chan Buddhism (<span class="chinese-char">禪宗</span>)</strong> — The Tang saw the full maturation of Chinese Buddhism, including the Chan (Zen) school and the integration of Buddhist and <a href="/taoism/">Daoist</a> thought</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/folk-arts/">Performing arts</a></strong> — Court lion dances, music, and theatrical traditions flourished, influencing folk performance arts for centuries</li>
        <li><strong>Printing</strong> — The world's earliest known printed book (Diamond Sutra, 868 CE) was produced during the Tang, beginning the revolution in information technology that would transform Chinese culture</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/martial-arts/">Martial arts</a></strong> — The Shaolin Temple's martial tradition reached prominence after warrior monks aided Li Shimin in founding the Tang Dynasty</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="song">
      <h2>Song Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">宋朝</span>, 960–1279 CE)</h2>
      <p>The Song — divided into <strong>Northern Song</strong> (960–1127, capital Kaifeng) and <strong>Southern Song</strong> (1127–1279, capital Lin'an/Hangzhou) — was China's most economically advanced and intellectually refined pre-modern dynasty. While militarily weaker than the Tang, it surpassed all predecessors in commerce, technology, art, and philosophical sophistication.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="/bazi/">BaZi perfected</a></strong> — Xu Ziping (<span class="chinese-char">徐子平</span>) added the Day Pillar and the Hour Pillar, completing the Four Pillars of Destiny system still used today. This Song Dynasty refinement is why the method is sometimes called the "Ziping method."</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/fengshui/">Feng shui</a></strong> — The Compass School (理氣派) matured during the Song, with the Luopan compass becoming an essential tool. Lai Buyi (<span class="chinese-char">賴布衣</span>) and other Song masters established methods still practised today.</li>
        <li><strong>Neo-Confucianism</strong> — Zhu Xi (<span class="chinese-char">朱熹</span>) synthesised Confucian, Buddhist, and <a href="/taoism/">Daoist</a> philosophy into the intellectual framework that dominated Chinese thought through the Ming Dynasty</li>
        <li><strong>Four Great Inventions</strong> — Moveable type printing (Bi Sheng, c. 1040), the magnetic compass, gunpowder weapons, and refined paper-making all reached maturity during the Song</li>
        <li><strong>Commercial revolution</strong> — The world's first paper money, sophisticated banking, and maritime trade networks made the Song the world's most advanced commercial economy</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/spring-festival/#kaigong-lishi">Kaigong Lishi origins</a></strong> — The Southern Song <em>買市</em> custom in Lin'an, documented by Zhou Mi, is the precursor to the modern red envelope tradition</li>
        <li><strong>Landscape painting</strong> — Song landscape painting (<span class="chinese-char">山水畫</span>) reached heights of philosophical depth and technical mastery that remain the benchmark of Chinese visual art</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="yuan">
      <h2>Yuan Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">元朝</span>, 1271–1368 CE)</h2>
      <p>The Yuan was established by Kublai Khan (<span class="chinese-char">忽必烈</span>) after the Mongol conquest of China. As a foreign-ruled dynasty, it represents a complex chapter in Chinese cultural history — a period of both cultural suppression and unexpected cultural productivity.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Yuan drama (<span class="chinese-char">元曲</span>)</strong> — Excluded from government service by Mongol policies, Chinese literati turned to theatrical writing, creating the golden age of Chinese drama. Guan Hanqing (<span class="chinese-char">關漢卿</span>) and other playwrights produced masterworks of the <em>zaju</em> (<span class="chinese-char">雜劇</span>) genre.</li>
        <li><strong>Astronomy</strong> — Guo Shoujing (<span class="chinese-char">郭守敬</span>) created the Shoushi calendar (1281), the most accurate calendar in the world at that time, with a year length accurate to within 26 seconds of the modern value</li>
        <li><strong>Maritime connection</strong> — Marco Polo's travels and extensive trade networks connected Yuan China to the wider world, though the dynasty's foreign character created cultural tensions</li>
        <li><strong>Agricultural treatises</strong> — Wang Zhen's (<span class="chinese-char">王禎</span>) <em>Nongshu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">農書</span>, 1313) documented agricultural techniques and their relationship to the <a href="/calendar/">solar terms</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="ming">
      <h2>Ming Dynasty (<span class="chinese-char">明朝</span>, 1368–1644 CE)</h2>
      <p>The Ming Dynasty — founded by Zhu Yuanzhang (<span class="chinese-char">朱元璋</span>), a former peasant and Buddhist monk — restored Han Chinese rule and consciously revived pre-Yuan cultural traditions. It was the last dynasty ruled by Han Chinese and represents the culmination of many cultural traditions discussed on this site.</p>
      <h3>Cultural Contributions</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="/hanfu/">Hanfu restoration</a></strong> — Zhu Yuanzhang explicitly decreed the revival of Han Chinese clothing, abolishing Mongol styles and restoring Tang-Song forms with Ming innovations</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/tcm/">Bencao Gangmu</a></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">本草綱目</span>) — Li Shizhen's encyclopaedic materia medica (1578), cataloguing 1,892 medicinal substances, remains a landmark of Chinese medical literature</li>
        <li><strong>Zheng He's voyages</strong> — Admiral Zheng He (<span class="chinese-char">鄭和</span>) led seven maritime expeditions (1405–1433) reaching Southeast Asia, India, Arabia, and East Africa with fleets of hundreds of ships — the largest naval expeditions in history before the modern era</li>
        <li><strong>The Four Great Classical Novels</strong> — Three of China's four greatest novels were written or compiled during the Ming: <em>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</em>, <em>Water Margin</em>, and <em>Journey to the West</em></li>
        <li><strong>Porcelain</strong> — Jingdezhen blue-and-white porcelain (<span class="chinese-char">青花瓷</span>) reached its artistic peak, becoming China's most famous export worldwide</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/fengshui/">Feng shui</a> texts</strong> — Major compilations and commentaries on classical feng shui methods were produced during the Ming</li>
        <li><strong><a href="/spring-festival/">Spring couplets</a></strong> — Emperor Taizu popularised the practice of hanging red paper spring couplets, completing the evolution from ancient peachwood charms to the red paper tradition</li>
        <li><strong>Agricultural science</strong> — Xu Guangqi's (<span class="chinese-char">徐光啟</span>) <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> (1639) synthesised centuries of agricultural knowledge mapped to the <a href="/calendar/">solar terms</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

